{"id":"2301.10647","submitter":"Tamir Bendory","authors":"Tamir Bendory, Dan Edidin, and Ivan Gonzalez","title":"Finite alphabet phase retrieval","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.IT eess.SP math.AG math.IT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider the finite alphabet phase retrieval problem: recovering a signal\nwhose entries lie in a small alphabet of possible values from its Fourier\nmagnitudes. This problem arises in the celebrated technology of X-ray\ncrystallography to determine the atomic structure of biological molecules. Our\nmain result states that for generic values of the alphabet, two signals have\nthe same Fourier magnitudes if and only if several partitions have the same\ndifference sets. Thus, the finite alphabet phase retrieval problem reduces to\nthe combinatorial problem of determining a signal from those difference sets.\nNotably, this result holds true when one of the letters of the alphabet is\nzero, namely, for sparse signals with finite alphabet, which is the situation\nin X-ray crystallography.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 25 Jan 2023 15:34:51 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 7 Apr 2023 06:01:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-10"}
